SIMPLE: periwinkle
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Periwinkle
<hw>Per"i*win`kle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From AS.
<ets>pinewincla</ets> a shellfish, in which <ets>pine-</ets> is fr. L.
<ets>pina</ets>, <ets>pinna</ets>, a kind of mussel, akin to Gr. <?/.
Cf. <er>Winkle</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any small marine
gastropod shell of the genus <gen>Littorina</gen>. The common European
species (<spn>Littorina littorea</spn>), in Europe extensively used as
food, has recently become naturalized abundantly on the American coast.
See <er>Littorina</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In America the name is often applied to several large
univalves, as <spn>Fulgur carica</spn>, and <spn>Fulgur
canaliculata</spn>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Periwinkle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Periwinkle
<hw>Per"i*win`kle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>pervenke</ets>, AS.
<ets>pervince</ets>, fr. L. <ets>pervinca</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A trailing herb of the genus
<gen>Vinca</gen>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The common perwinkle (<spn>Vinca minor</spn>) has
opposite evergreen leaves and solitary blue or white flowers in their
axils. In America it is often miscalled <altname>myrtle</altname>. See
under <er>Myrtle</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Perjenet</ent>⟦br⟧
